# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: baltimore-terrapins
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-baltimore-terrapins-season] The 1914 Baltimore Terrapins season was a season in American baseball.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-baltimore-terrapins-season] They finished in third place in the Federal League, 4½ games behind the Indianapolis Hoosiers.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1914 throughout the world.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] The **1914 World Series** was the championship series of Major League Baseball's 1914 season.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] The 11th edition of the World Series, it was played between the American League (AL) champion and defending World Series champion Philadelphia Athletics and the National League (NL) champion Boston Braves.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] The "Miracle Braves" were in last place on July 4, then won the National League pennant by 10+1⁄2 games.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] The Braves' relatively unknown starting trio of pitchers, with a combined career record of 285–245, outperformed the Athletics' vaunted rotation (929–654) in all four games.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] Hank Gowdy hit .545 (6 of 11) with five extra-base hits and also drew five walks for Boston in the series and made the difference in Games 1 and 3.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] Adding to their supposed disadvantages, the Braves arguably lacked a notable home-field advantage.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] They had abandoned their 43-year-old home field South End Grounds in August 1914, choosing to rent from the Boston Red Sox at Fenway Park while awaiting construction of Braves Field (1915).
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] Thus their home games in this Series were also at Fenway.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] This was the first official four-game sweep in World Series history.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] The Chicago Cubs had defeated the Detroit Tigers four games to none in 1907, but Game 1 had ended in a tie before the Cubs won the next four in a row.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] Cohan through bookmaker Sport Sullivan, who was also implicated in the 1919 Black Sox scandal.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] Chief Bender and Eddie Plank jumped to the rival Federal League for the 1915 season.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] Mack unloaded most of his other high-priced stars soon after and, within two years, the A's posted the worst winning percentage in modern history (even worse than the 1962 New York Mets and the 2024 Chicago White Sox).
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] Because an AL team had won the last four World Series (the A's had represented the AL in three out of those four), the A's were heavily favored.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] The fact that the Braves had been in last place in July before coming back to win the pennant contributed to the perception that the AL was simply superior to the NL.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] The A's roster boasted five future Hall of Famers and many agreed they were the better team on paper.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] A story told about Connie Mack during the 1914 season reflects this attitude among the A's that the Braves would be pushovers.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] That year, Mack gave star pitcher Chief Bender the week off and told him to scout the Braves personally.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] After having won 26 games, Dick Rudolph scattered five hits while striking out eight as the Braves won the opener in convincing fashion against the Athletics' ace, Chief Bender.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] Catcher Hank Gowdy had a single, double and triple as well as a walk in leading Boston's offensive attack.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] He was also on the back end of a double steal in the eighth inning, with Butch Schmidt's steal of home the Braves' final run.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] In Tom Meany's 1950 book *Baseball's Greatest Teams*, with one chapter discussing what the author thought each of the then 16 major league teams' single most outstanding season was, the chapter on the Boston Braves was naturally on their one world championship year, 1914.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] Meany may also have been the source for the sensational sidelight that Stallings' motive for this may have been the rumor that the A's may have sabotaged the Shibe Park visiting clubhouse (with war clouds gathering in Europe as World War I was just beginning).
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] Bill James, Boston's other 26-game winner, hooked up against Philadelphia's Eddie Plank in a classic pitcher's duel.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] James allowed only three base runners in the first eight innings, picking off two of them in holding Philadelphia scoreless.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] Plank matched him until the ninth, when Amos Strunk lost Charlie Deal's fly ball in the sun for a double.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] Deal then stole third, and scored on a two-out single by Les Mann.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] James walked two batters in the ninth, but got Eddie Murphy to ground into a game-ending double play to give Boston a 2–0 advantage in the series coming back home to Fenway.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] Lefty Tyler of the Braves went up against Bullet Joe Bush in a 12-inning thriller.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] Frank "Home Run" Baker's two-out single in the tenth plated two runs to give the Athletics a 4–2 lead and a seeming victory to get them back in the series.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] But Hank Gowdy led off the bottom of the tenth with a home run, and the Braves then tied the game on Joe Connolly's sacrifice fly later in the inning.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] Game 2 winner Bill James, coming on in relief for Boston in the 11th, earned the win after Gowdy led off the bottom of the 12th with a double and pinch-runner Les Mann scored when Bush threw wildly to third on Herbie Moran's bunt, giving the Braves a commanding 3–0 series lead.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] Johnny Evers' two-out, two-run single in the bottom of the fifth broke a 1–1 tie and the collective backs of the heavily favored Athletics as the "Miracle Braves" completed their improbable sweep.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] Game 1 winner Dick Rudolph allowed only one base-runner after Evers' tie-breaking hit and struck out seven in notching his second win of the series.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] The powerful A's were held to a .172 team batting average and no home runs in the series.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] This was the only championship the Braves won during their time in Boston, as the team would move to Milwaukee, Wisconsin in 1953.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] They would make one more World Series appearance before the move in 1948, which they lost to the Cleveland Indians in six games.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] The Braves would win their next championship in 1957 over the New York Yankees in seven games, which would be the only championship they won in Milwaukee, as the team then moved to Atlanta in 1966.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1914-world-series] The Athletics would return to the World Series in 1929, and defeated the Chicago Cubs in five games.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1915-baltimore-terrapins-season] The **1915 Baltimore Terrapins season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1915-baltimore-terrapins-season] The Terrapins finished in 8th place in the Federal League, 40 games behind the Chicago Whales.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1915-baltimore-terrapins-season] After the season, both the team and the league folded.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1915-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1915 throughout the world.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1915-in-baseball] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/1954-in-baseball-p01] The following are the baseball events of the year 1954 throughout the world.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] The **American League of Professional Baseball Clubs**, known simply as the **American League** (**AL**), is the younger of two leagues constituting Major League Baseball (MLB) in the United States and Canada.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] It developed from the Western League, a minor league based in the Great Lakes states, which eventually aspired to major league status.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] It is sometimes called the **Junior Circuit** because it claimed Major League status for the 1901 season, 25 years after the formation of the National League (the "Senior Circuit").
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] Since 1903, the American League champion has played in the World Series against the National League champion with only two exceptions: 1904, when the NL champion New York Giants refused to play their AL counterpart, and 1994, when a players' strike resulted in the cancellation of the Series.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] Through 2025, American League teams have won 68 of the 121 World Series played since 1903.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] The New York Yankees have won 27 World Series and 41 American League titles, the most in major league history.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] The Philadelphia/Kansas City/Oakland Athletics have won the second most AL titles with 15, followed by the Boston Red Sox with 14.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] For decades, Major League baseball clubs only played teams from their own league during the regular season and playoffs, with only the two pennant winners meeting in the World Series.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] The AL and NL also employed and trained their own umpires, who only worked regular season games in their own league.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] These differences resulted in the leagues developing slightly different strategies and styles of play.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] The American League was usually regarded as the less "traditional" league during the 20th century, a reputation most exemplified by the introduction of the designated hitter rule in 1973, which encouraged AL managers to largely abandon "smallball" tactics.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] Though both leagues agreed to be jointly governed by a commissioner in 1920, they remained separate business entities with their own presidents and management.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] This was the case until after the 1999 season, when the American League legally merged with the National League under the auspices of Major League Baseball, which now operates much like other North American professional sports leagues, albeit with two "leagues" instead of "conferences".
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] Originally a minor league known as the Western League, which existed from 1885 to 1899 with teams in mostly Great Lakes states, the league changed its name to the American League for the 1900 season and the next year developed into a second major league as a competitor to the older National League.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] This was prompted by the NL dropping four teams following the 1899 season after having absorbed its previous rival, the American Association, which disbanded in 1891 after ten seasons.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] In its early history of the late 1880s, the minor Western League struggled until 1894, when Ban Johnson became the president of the league.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] Johnson pushed the league to rise to major league status, after the name change to the American League was decided in a league meeting in Milwaukee, Wisconsin, at the former Republican Hotel.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] A historical marker is at the intersection of North Dr.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] Drive and West Kilbourn Avenue where the hotel once stood.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] In March 1904, Johnson moved the league's headquarters from Chicago to New York.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] Babe Ruth, noted as one of the most prolific hitters in Major League Baseball history, spent the majority of his career in the American League with the Boston Red Sox and the New York Yankees.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] From 1973 to 2022 The American League had one notable difference versus the rival National League, as it had the designated hitter rule.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] Under the rule, a team may use a batter in its lineup who is not in the field defensively, replacing the pitcher in the batting order, compared to the old rule that made it mandatory for the pitcher to bat.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] In the last two decades, the season schedule has allowed occasional interleague play.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] In 1969, the AL (and NL) were divided into East and West divisions, with a postseason playoff series for the pennant and the right to play in the World Series.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] Until the late 1970s, league umpires working behind home plate wore large, balloon-style chest protectors worn outside the shirt or coat, while their colleagues in the National League wore chest protectors inside the shirt or coat.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] In 1977, new umpires (including Steve Palermo) had to wear the inside chest protector, although those on staff wearing the outside protector could continue to do so.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] Most umpires made the switch to the inside protector, led by Don Denkinger in 1975 and Jim Evans the next year, although several did not, including Bill Haller, Russ Goetz, George Maloney, Bill Kunkel and Jerry Neudecker, who became the last full-time MLB umpire to use the outside protector in 1985.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] In 1998, the newly franchised Tampa Bay Devil Rays joined the league, and the Arizona Diamondbacks joined the National League: i.e., each league added a fifteenth team.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] An odd number of teams per league meant that at least one team in each league would have to be idle on any given day, or alternatively, that odd team out would have had to play an interleague game against its counterpart in the other league.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] The initial plan was to have three five-team divisions per league with inter-league play year-round—possibly as many as 30 interleague games per team each year.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] For various reasons, it soon seemed more practical to have an even number of teams in both leagues.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] The Milwaukee Brewers agreed to change leagues to become the National League's 16th team, moving from the AL Central to the NL Central.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] At the same time, the Detroit Tigers were moved from the AL East to the AL Central, making room for the Devil Rays in the East.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] Even after expansion, the American League then continued with 14 teams.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] This situation changed again in 2013 when the Houston Astros moved from the National League Central division to the American League West.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] The Astros had been in the NL for 51 years since beginning as an expansion team in 1962.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] Since their move, both leagues now consist of 15 teams.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] For the first 96 years, American League teams faced their National League counterparts only in exhibition games or in the World Series.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] Beginning in 1997, interleague games have been played during the regular season and count in the standings.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] As part of the agreement instituting interleague play, the designated-hitter rule was used only in games where the American League team is the home team, until the 2022 season, when the universal DH rule was implemented.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] In 2023, American League teams played 46 regular season interleague games against all 15 National League teams, 23 at home and 23 on the road.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] In 2000, the American League ended its status as a legally independent entity when the American and National Leagues were both merged into the legal entity Major League Baseball (MLB).
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] This left MLB as a single league, divided into two parts, also called leagues.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] This change in legal status had no effect on play, scheduling, and so forth.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] There were eight charter teams in 1901, the league's first year as a major league, and the next year the original Milwaukee Brewers (not to be confused with the current Milwaukee Brewers) moved to St.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] Louis Browns, and the year after the New York Highlanders replaced the disbanded original Baltimore Orioles.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] Those eight franchises constituted the league for 52 seasons until the Browns moved to Baltimore and took up the Orioles name.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] The first line is the transformation of the American League (AL) to a major league in 1901.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] The second line is the beginning of the expansion era in 1961.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] The third line marks the legal merger of the American and National Leagues into a single Major League Baseball in 2000.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] World Series championships are shown with a "•", American League Pennants before the World Series are shown with a "#", and American League Pennants who lost the World Series are shown with a "^".
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] No World Series was played in 1904, so the pennant winners for each league are indicated.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] Due to the 1994–95 Major League Baseball strike, there were no pennant or World Series winners in 1994, so this year is left blank.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] Following the 1999 season, the American and National Leagues were merged with Major League Baseball, and the leagues ceased to exist as business entities.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/american-league] The position of the American League President and National League President became honorary.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/baltimore-terrapins] The **Baltimore Terrapins** were a team in the short-lived Federal League of professional baseball from 1914 to 1915.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/baltimore-terrapins] Their brief existence led to litigation that led to an important legal precedent in baseball.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/baltimore-terrapins] The team played its home games at Terrapin Park.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/baltimore-terrapins] Most of the professional baseball teams in Baltimore have been called the Orioles, in reference to the Baltimore oriole bird.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/baltimore-terrapins] There was already a minor league Baltimore Orioles, and the new Federal League club built their ballpark directly across the street from the Orioles park.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/baltimore-terrapins] The new club chose to call itself the Baltimore Terrapins, after the diamondback terrapin, the state reptile of Maryland.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/baltimore-terrapins] That nickname would later become primarily associated with the University of Maryland, College Park sports teams called the Maryland Terrapins.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/baltimore-terrapins] Baltimore gathered for spring training in Southern Pines, North Carolina at the Southern Pines Golf Club, previously used by the Philadelphia Phillies in 1909 and 1910.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/baltimore-terrapins] Terrapins manager Otto Knabe had played for these Phillies teams and trained in Southern Pines.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/baltimore-terrapins] While the 1914 team posted a respectable 84–70 record and finished only 4½ games out of first place under player-manager Otto Knabe, the team was less than successful at the box office, even though four of the eight teams in the league (Chicago, Brooklyn, Pittsburgh, and St.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/baltimore-terrapins] Louis) were competing with one and even two (Chicago and St.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/baltimore-terrapins] Louis) other major league teams in the same cities.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/baltimore-terrapins] In an attempt to turn this situation around and attract a marquee player to help them at the box office, the 1915 team recruited Chief Bender of the American League champion Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/baltimore-terrapins] The Athletics had sold off several future Hall-of-Famers like Eddie Plank, Eddie Collins and Frank "Home Run" Baker after being swept by the surprising Boston Braves in the 1914 World Series.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/baltimore-terrapins] Bender had come off an impressive 17–3 season where he compiled seven shutouts and a 2.26 ERA in 1914.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/baltimore-terrapins] However, his 1915 season at Baltimore was a low point of his Hall of Fame career when he slumped to a 4–16 record, no shutouts, and a 3.99 ERA.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/baltimore-terrapins] Baltimore's collapse to a 47–107 record, 40 games out of first, was overshadowed only by the collapse of Bender's former team who went from a 99–53 league championship season to a dismal 43–109 record, 58½ games out of first in 1915.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/baltimore-terrapins] Bender and the Baltimore Terrapins never made a full recovery from 1915.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/baltimore-terrapins] The incident did show the Federal League could compete seriously with the National League and American League on a professional baseball level and led to the buy-out truce which ended the Federal League for good.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/baltimore-terrapins] However, the Baltimore team's owners were not offered a part in this buyout.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/baltimore-terrapins] When the Federal League started, the Terrapins severely cut into the minor league Baltimore Orioles' attendance, causing financial problems for the owner.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/baltimore-terrapins] As a result, several players, including the young left-handed pitcher Babe Ruth, were offered for sale to major league teams.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/baltimore-terrapins] Ruth's contract was purchased by the Boston Red Sox, after being turned down by Connie Mack and the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/baltimore-terrapins] In 1914, Ruth began his career with the Red Sox of the rival American League.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/baltimore-terrapins] After the demise of the Federal League and the Terrapins, Baltimore would not see major league baseball again until 1954, when the former St.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/baltimore-terrapins] Louis Browns moved into town and became the present-day Baltimore Orioles.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/baltimore-terrapins] As the Terrapins' owners were not offered any part of the buyout offer made to most Federal League teams by the American and National Leagues, they decided to sue, alleging that the buyout was in violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/baltimore-terrapins] Supreme Court deciding that the scheduling and playing of "base ball games" did not constitute "interstate commerce" in any sense envisioned by the Framers of the United States Constitution; therefore, the Sherman Act and other federal laws and regulations did not apply to baseball.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/baltimore-terrapins] National League*, was not ultimately decided until 1922.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/baltimore-terrapins] The minor league Orioles moved into Terrapin Park, a wooden ballpark.
[src:baltimore-terrapins/baltimore-terrapins] This move began a chain of events which would eventually lead to the return of major league baseball to Baltimore.
